Perform an authenticated advanced scan

By choosing the Advanced Scan template, you will see three primary configuration tabs.

  1. Settings
  2. Credentials
  3. Plugins

 

Figure - zoom in


Under the Settings tab, which is the default one, you will see a set of options such as the Name of the scan, the Description of the scan, the Targets where you can define an IP range or a single IP address you would like to scan, etc.

Place 127.0.0.1 as your target address.

Figure - zoom in


Under the Credentials tab, you will get three options Nessus can utilize to authenticate with a system and perform scanning activities. Those options are Windows, SSH, and SNMPv3.

We will use the SSH option to scan a Linux host.

Figure - zoom in


Under the Plugins tab, search for ubuntu in the Filter/search bar, click on the Ubuntu Local Security Checks, then hit the Save button.

Figure - zoom in


Hitting the Save button will save your scan and make it ready to launch against the set target. Now, you can go ahead and launch your scan.

Figure - zoom in


The scan will take some time to finish (approximately 15 minutes), and once it completes, you will see the Scan Details along with a breakdown chart of the discovered vulnerabilities.

Figure - zoom in


Clicking on the Vulnerabilities tab, you'll see a detailed list of the discovered vulnerabilities sorted by severity.

Figure - zoom in


Clicking on one of the vulnerabilities from the above list will show you a detailed description which we will cover in the next lab use case.
